x4freetext: Yu.N.Kopatch
D.Schwalm, P.Thirolf
F.Goennenwein
Darmstadt-Heidelberg Crystal Ball
spectrometer as homogeneous and highly granulated 4PI
neutron detector, combined with an efficient detection
system for fission fragments and ternary particles.
Crystal  ball (CB) is dense spherical package of 162
NaI(Tl) crystals of 20 cm long, of high gamma-ray
detection efficiency (>90%). Simultaneously
to gamma-rays, the CB registers neutrons from fission
with a efficiency of about 60% for En>= 2MeV, dropping
down to about 50% for En below 0.5 MeV.
Inside the CB a spherical space of 50 cm diameter
the assembly of particle detectors was mounted in
CH4-filled spherical aluminum vessel, contained the
Cf-252 sample located at the center.
Kinematic spectrometer CODIS consists of
Frisch-gridded 4-pi twin ionization chamber IC for
measuring fission-fragment energies and emission angles
and of a ring of 12 deltaE-E telescopes made from
deltaE IC and silicon p-i-n diodes, with a solid
angle of pi/4, surrounding one half of the fragment IC
for measuring the LCPs. Angular resolutions FWHM =<5deg
for both the fragments and LCPs.
Cf-252 sample of 4.x 10**3 fissions/s on thin backing.
Gamma-rays were separated from the neutrons by
time-of-flight measurement from the Cf-252 sample to
the crystals -distance 25 cm.
Coincidences between the ternary particles,
fission fragments, and neutrons and gamma-rays.
Simultaneously to TF events, 7.x 10**7 binary fissions
were recorded, the data acquisition rate for this event
type being reduced by a factor of 1/64.
Calibration of the CB pulse-height spectra in
terms of gamma-energy was performed with various
gamma-ray sources, following standard procedures.
Threshold corresponding to 100 keV gamma-energy was set
in all the pulse-height spectra.

Li yield was obtained from Gaussian fit to measured
energy spectrum with fixed E-LCP = 14.3+-1.0 MeV and
FWHM=14.3+-1.0 MeV from  C.Wagemans, in Particle
Emission from Nuclei, edited by D.N.Poenaru+,CRC Press,
Boca Raton,1989, chapter 3.
For the H-3 spectrum there is also an upper limit of
11.5 MeV for full energy registration due to the
limited thickness of the silicon detectors.
Energy and angular LCP spectra are given on
Fig.3 of J,PR/C,65,044614,2002 as counts.
Neutron angular distributions measured in
coincidence with LCP, (projections on zx and xy planes)
are given on Figs.5,6 of J,PR/C,65,044614,2002 as
counts.
